UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 including expulsion from school, for a student who is determined by the board
2 to have:
3 1. Possessed prescription drugs or controlled substances for the purpose of
4 sale or distribution at a school under the board's jurisdiction;
5 2. Physically assaulted or battered or abused educational personnel or other
6 students at a school or school function under the board's jurisdiction; or
7 3. Physically assaulted, battered, or abused educational personnel or other
8 students off school property and the incident is likely to substantially
9 disrupt the educational process.
10 (3) (a) The board may modify the expulsion requirement and length for students on a
11 case-by-case basis, except the length of expulsion shall be at least twelve (12)
12 months for a violation set forth in subsection (2)(a) of this section.
13 (b) Nothing in this section shall prohibit a board from expelling a student for
14 longer than twelve (12) months.
15 (c) A board that has expelled a student from the student's regular school setting
16 shall provide or ensure that educational services are provided to the student in
17 an appropriate alternative program or setting, unless the board has made a
18 determination, on the record, supported by clear and convincing evidence, that
19 the expelled student posed a threat to the safety of other students or school
20 staff and could not be placed into a state-funded agency program. Behavior
21 which constitutes a threat shall include but not be limited to the physical
22 assault, battery, or abuse of others; the threat of physical force; being under
23 the influence of drugs or alcohol; the use, possession, sale, or transfer of drugs
24 or alcohol; the carrying, possessing, or transfer of weapons or dangerous
25 instruments; and any other behavior which may endanger the safety of others.
26 Other intervention services as indicated for each student may be provided by
27 the board or by agreement with the appropriate state or community agency. A
Page 2 of 8
XXXX 3/3/2026 11:06 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 state agency that provides the service shall be responsible for the cost.
2 (d) 1. a. In lieu of expelling a student, or upon the expiration of a student's
3 expulsion, a superintendent may place a student into an alternative
4 program or setting indefinitely if the superintendent determines
5 placement of the student in his or her regular school setting is
6 likely to substantially disrupt the education process or constitutes a
7 threat to the safety of other students or school staff.
8 b. Placements under subdivision a. of this subparagraph that
9 exceed one (1) calendar year shall require an annual review by
10 the superintendent. Significant consideration shall be given to
11 the safety and potential disruption to the educational process for
12 all students in determining whether a change in placement shall
13 occur.
14 c. Action shall not be taken under subdivision a. of this
15 subparagraph, and a change in placement shall not be made
16 under subdivision b. of this subparagraph,[The action shall not
17 be taken] until the parent, guardian, or other person having legal
18 custody or control of the student has had an opportunity to have a
19 hearing before the board or an appeals committee as described in
20 subparagraph 2. of this paragraph.
21 2. The board may adopt a policy to establish an appeals committee and
22 delegate the authority to hold hearings and hear appeals made under
23 this paragraph to that committee. Decisions of the appeals committee
24 may be appealed to the local board of education by the parent,
25 guardian, or other person having legal custody or control of the
26 student.
27 3. The alternative program or setting may be provided virtually.
Page 3 of 8
XXXX 3/3/2026 11:06 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 4. Notwithstanding any other statute or administrative regulation to the
2 contrary, students placed in an alternative program or setting under this
3 paragraph shall be counted in attendance and membership for state
4 funding purposes in the same manner as other students participating in
5 alternative programs of the district.
6 5. Students placed in an alternative program or setting under this paragraph
7 shall be subject to compulsory attendance requirements under KRS
8 Chapter 159 and applicable local board policy.
9 6. Following the initial alternative placement of a student under this
10 paragraph, the board shall review the alternative program or setting
11 placement at least once per year and determine if the placement should
12 be continued in accordance with subparagraph 1. of this paragraph.
13 (4) For purposes of this subsection, "charges" means substantiated behavior that falls
14 within the grounds for suspension or expulsion enumerated in subsection (1) of this
15 section, including behavior committed by a student while enrolled in a private or
16 public school, or in a school within another state. A school board may adopt a
17 policy providing that, if a student is suspended or expelled for any reason or faces
18 charges that may lead to suspension or expulsion but withdraws prior to a hearing
19 from any public or private school in this or any other state, the receiving district
20 may review the details of the charges, suspension, or expulsion and determine if the
21 student will be admitted, and if so, what conditions may be imposed upon the
22 admission, which may include placement of the student into an alternative program
23 or setting as described in subsection (3)(d) of this section.
24 (5) (a) School administrators, teachers, or other school personnel may immediately
25 remove or cause to be removed threatening or violent students from a
26 classroom setting or from the district transportation system pending any
27 further disciplinary action that may occur. Each board of education shall adopt
Page 4 of 8
XXXX 3/3/2026 11:06 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 a policy to assure the implementation of this section and to assure the safety
2 of the students and staff.
3 (b) Except as described in subsection (10) of this section:
4 1. A principal may establish procedures for a student's removal from and
5 reentry to the classroom when the student's behavior disrupts the
6 classroom environment and education process or the student challenges
7 the authority of a supervising adult. In addition to removal, the student
8 shall be subject to further discipline for the behavior consistent with the
9 school's code of conduct.
10 2. A student who is removed from the same classroom three (3) times
11 within a thirty (30) day period shall be considered chronically disruptive
12 and may be suspended from school in accordance with this section, and
13 no other basis for suspension shall be deemed necessary.
14 3. At any time during the school year, for a student who has been removed
15 from the classroom under this paragraph, a principal may require a
16 review of the classroom issues with the teacher and the parent, guardian,
17 or other person having legal custody or control of the student and
18 determine a course of action for the teacher and student regarding the
19 student's continued placement in the classroom.
20 4. At any time during the school year, a principal may permanently remove
21 a student from a classroom for the remainder of the school year if the
22 principal determines the student's continued placement in the classroom
23 will chronically disrupt the education process for other students.
24 5. When a student is removed from a classroom under this paragraph
25 temporarily or permanently, the principal shall determine the placement
26 of the student in lieu of that classroom, which may include but is not
27 limited to:
Page 5 of 8
XXXX 3/3/2026 11:06 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 a. Another classroom in that school; or
2 b. An alternative program or setting, which may be provided
3 virtually, as approved by the superintendent.
4 6. Any permanent action by a principal under this paragraph shall be
5 subject to an appeal process in accordance with a policy adopted by the
6 board.
7 7. Policies compliant with this paragraph shall be included in the code of
8 behavior and discipline adopted by the board of education under KRS
9 158.148 and the policies adopted by the school council under KRS
10 160.345.
11 (6) A student shall not be suspended from the common schools until after at least the
12 following due process procedures have been provided:
13 (a) The student has been given oral or written notice of the charge or charges
14 against him or her which constitute cause for suspension;
15 (b) The student has been given an explanation of the evidence of the charge or
16 charges if the student denies them; and
17 (c) The student has been given an opportunity to present his or her own version of
18 the facts relating to the charge or charges.
19 These due process procedures shall precede any suspension from the common
20 schools unless immediate suspension is essential to protect persons or property or to
21 avoid disruption of the ongoing academic process. In such cases, the due process
22 procedures outlined above shall follow the suspension as soon as practicable, but no
23 later than three (3) school days after the suspension.
24 (7) (a) The superintendent, principal, assistant principal, or head teacher of any
25 school may suspend a student but shall report the action in writing
26 immediately to the superintendent and to the parent, guardian, or other person
27 having legal custody or control of the student.
Page 6 of 8
XXXX 3/3/2026 11:06 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 (b) 1. The board of education of any school district may expel or extend the
2 expulsion of any student for misconduct as described in subsection (1)
3 of this section, but the action shall not be taken until the parent,
4 guardian, or other person having legal custody or control of the student
5 has had an opportunity to have a hearing before the board. The decision
6 of the board shall be final.
7 2. Within thirty (30) days prior to the end of a student's expulsion, the
8 board shall review the details of the expulsion and current factors and
9 circumstances, including if ending the expulsion will substantially
10 disrupt the education process or constitute a threat to the safety of
11 students or school staff, to determine if the expulsion shall be extended
12 for a period not to exceed twelve (12) months.
13 3. The expulsion review process shall be used prior to the end of each
14 expulsion period until the board ends the expulsion or the student is no
15 longer subject to compulsory attendance under KRS 159.010.
16 4. Each board of education shall adopt a policy for implementation of the
17 process described in this paragraph.
18 (8) (a) Suspension of exceptional children, as defined in KRS 157.200, shall be
19 considered a change of educational placement if:
20 1. The child is removed for more than ten (10) consecutive days during a
21 school year; or
22 2. The child is subjected to a series of removals that constitute a pattern
23 because the removals accumulate to more than ten (10) school days
24 during a school year and because of other factors, such as the length of
25 each removal, the total amount of time the child is removed, and the
26 proximity of removals to one another.
27 (b) The admissions and release committee shall meet to review the placement and
Page 7 of 8
XXXX 3/3/2026 11:06 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 21
1 make a recommendation for continued placement or a change in placement
2 and determine whether regular suspension or expulsion procedures apply.
3 Additional evaluations shall be completed, if necessary.
4 (c) If the admissions and release committee determines that an exceptional child's
5 behavior is related to his or her disability, the child shall not be suspended any
6 further or expelled unless the current placement could result in injury to the
7 child, other children, or the educational personnel, in which case an
8 appropriate alternative placement shall be provided that will provide for the
9 child's educational needs and will provide a safe learning and teaching
10 environment for all. If the admissions and release committee determines that
11 the behavior is not related to the disability, the local educational agency may
12 pursue its regular suspension or expulsion procedure for the child, if the
13 behavior so warrants. However, educational services shall not be terminated
14 during a period of expulsion and during a suspension after a student is
15 suspended for more than a total of ten (10) days during a school year. A
16 district may seek temporary injunctive relief through the courts if the parent
17 and the other members of the admissions and release committee cannot agree
18 upon a placement and the current placement will likely result in injury to the
19 student or others.
20 (9) Suspension of primary school students shall be considered only in exceptional cases
21 where there are safety issues for the child or others.
22 (10) Any action under this section related to students with disabilities shall be in
23 compliance with applicable federal law.
24 (11) Nothing in this section shall be interpreted or construed to preclude the
25 requirements contained in KRS 158.305 or 158.4416.
